you choose to take part in this kind of study? This book explores the hidden world of pharmaceutical testing on healthy volunteers. Drawing on two years of fieldwork in clinics across the country and 268 interviews with participants and staff, it illustrates how decisions to take part in such studies are often influenced by poverty and lack of employment opportunities. It shows that healthy participants are typically recruited from African American and Latino/a communities, and that they are often serial participants, who obtain a significant portion of their income from these trials. This book reveals not only how social inequality fundamentally shapes these drug trials, but it also depicts the important validity concerns inherent in this mode of testing new pharmaceuticals. These highly controlled studies bear little resemblance to real-world conditions, and everyone involved is incentivized to game the system, ultimately making new drugs appear safer than they really are. Adverse Events provides an unprecedented view of the intersection of racial inequalities with pharmaceutical testing, signaling the dangers of this research enterprise to both social justice and public health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aDrugsxTestingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEqualityxHealth aspectszUnited States. 0aHuman experimentation in medicinexMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aRacism in medicinezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aUnited States.  aclinic.  aclinical trial culture.  aclinical trials.  aclinics.  aconfinement.  aconsumption.  adecision making.  ademographics.  adrug development.  aeconomic interests.  aeconomic motivations.  aeconomic need.  aeconomic risk.  aepistemology.  ahealth-promoting behavior.  ahealthy volunteers.  a